Η μαθηματική και η τέχνη σχετίζονται με πολλούς τρόπους. Η μαθηματική έχει περιγραφεί ως μια τέχνη που ενδιαφέρεται για την ομορφιά. Η μαθηματική μπορεί να αναγνωριστεί σε τέχνες όπως η μουσική, ο χορός, η ζωγραφική, η αρχιτεκτονική, η γλυπτική και τα υφάσματα. Αυτό το άρθρο επικεντρώνεται, ωστόσο, στη μαθηματική στις εικαστικές τέχνες.
Η μαθηματική και η τέχνη έχουν μια μακρά ιστορική σχέση. Οι καλλιτέχνες χρησιμοποίησαν τη μαθηματική από τον 4ο αιώνα π.Χ., όταν ο ελληνικής καταγωγής γλύπτης Πολύκλειτος έγραψε τον Κανόνα του, προτείνοντας αναλογίες που υποθέτεται ότι βασίζονταν στην αναλογία 1:√2 για τον ιδανικό γυμνό άνδρα. Έχουν γίνει συνεχείς δημοφιλείς ισχυρισμοί για τη χρήση της χρυσής αναλογίας στην αρχαία τέχνη και αρχιτεκτονική, χωρίς αξιόπιστες αποδείξεις. Κατά την Ιταλική Αναγέννηση, ο Λούκα Πατσιόλι έγραψε το επιδραστικό έργο "De divina proportione" (1509), με εικονογραφήσεις από τον Λεονάρντο ντα Βίντσι, για τη χρήση της χρυσής αναλογίας στην τέχνη. "Good Kid" è una raccolta di canzoni musicali pubblicata il 25 settembre del 2021 dalla ragazza di 16 anni di Los Angeles, Billie Eilish. La raccolta comprende una serie di canzoni che Billie ha scritto e prodotte insieme a suonatori e musicisti che fanno parte della sua squadra di supporto. Le prime dieci canzoni sono state pubblicate come singoli da Billie tra il gennaio e il marzo del 2020, mentre le altre dieci sono state pubblicate in un album nel gennaio del 2021. La raccolta ha ricevuto accoglienze positive, sia dalla critica che dalla comunità musicale online. La raccolta è stata pubblicata da Darkroom/Interscope Records.

"Good Kid" è la seconda raccolta musicale pubblicata da Billie Eilish, dopo che la ragazza aveva pubblicato la sua prima raccolta musicale, quando aveva solo 14 anni, intitolata "Don't Smile at Me". La raccolta è stata pubblicata dal suo stesso label Darkroom e dall'etichetta discografica Interscope Records nel gennaio del 2020. 

"Good Kid" ha ricevuto diversi riconoscimenti. Nel marzo del 2020, la raccolta ha vinto un Grammy per la Miglior canzone popolare per bambini ed è stata nominata per l'Oscar della Miglior colonna sonora. Nel settembre del 2020, la raccolta ha vinto lo Streamy Award per la Miglior colonna sonora popolare. Nell'ottobre del 2020, la raccolta è stata nominata per il BRIT Award della Migliore nuova voce in musica pop. Nel novembre del 2020, la raccolta è stata nominata per l'ASCAP Award della Migliore colonna sonora popolare e ha vinto lo Streamy Award per la Miglior colonna sonora popolare. Nell'ottobre del 2020, la raccolta ha vinto un Teen Choice Award nella categoria Miglior colonna sonora popolare. Nell'aprile del 2021, la raccolta è stata nominata per lo Grammy Award della Migliore colonna sonore popolare. Nell'ottobre del 2021, Billie Eilish ha vinto due premi nella categoria Miglior album nel suo album precedente, Happier Than Ever."

The exhibition is a celebration of Banksy’s career and features some of his most iconic pieces, including “Love Is In The Air,” which was created in response to the death of George Floyd in 2020, and “Giant Balloon,” a large-scale sculpture made from used helium balloons that was installed in New York City in 2018.

Visitors can also see Banksy’s take on the biblical story of creation in the form of his “Tree of Knowledge” series, which features a giant apple with a snake wrapped around it. The exhibition is on display at the Harvard Art Museums until March 27, 2022.

Δελτίο Τύπου:

Hellenic Air Force (HAF) – General Military Authority (GMA) Interrogation Manual

Introduction:
This manual is intended for use by Air Force interrogation personnel during the initial phase of intelligence interrogation of enemy personnel captured in military operations in accordance with the provisions of international agreements and laws of war. 

The interrogation procedure may be conducted either by an interrogation team or by a single interrogator. An interrogation team consists of a single interrogator and an interpreter. It is recommended that at least two interrogators should be present when an interpreter is not available.

Definitions:
* Interrogation: Any activity involving the collection and exchange of information by questioning, observation, or other means, as authorized by military necessity, to obtain information on enemy operations, plans, dispositions, and intentions. 
* Intelligence: Information relating to the enemy’s capabilities and intentions obtained by direct observation or from any other source, including captured enemy personnel, documents, weapons, equipment and facilities. 
* Enemy Personnel: Members of an armed force, organized armed groups and individuals who participate directly in hostilities, whether individually or collectively, including captured personnel. 
* Captured Enemy Personnel: Persons who have been captured by ground forces or naval forces during military operations. 
* Intelligence Information: All information collected on the enemy’s capabilities, dispositions, intentions, or activities which may be useful to the Armed Forces in planning operations and in making operational decisions. This includes information on enemy weaponry and equipment. 
* General Military Authority (GMA): The legal authority that authorizes military operations under international law and which provides the legal framework within which military operations are conducted. 
* Military Intelligence (MI): Information generated by an organization that is responsible for collecting and analyzing intelligence relating to enemy capabilities and intentions for the purpose of providing intelligence support to military operations. 
* Intelligence Requirements: The intelligence needed for planning operations and making operational decisions. 
* Intelligence Requirements Analysis (IRA): A process used to identify intelligence requirements based on intelligence analysis of available information and operational plans. 
* Intelligence Plan (IP): A plan developed based on intelligence requirements analysis that outlines how intelligence will be collected and analyzed in order to provide intelligence support to military operations. 
* Source Operations: The organization and execution of a series of actions designed to obtain information about an enemy force or activity from an informed source or sources within that force or activity. The objective is to obtain specific information relevant to intelligence requirements analysis. Source operations are conducted in accordance with GMA rules. 
* Source Interrogation: A process used to obtain specific information relevant to intelligence requirements analysis from a single source in a structured interview format. Source interrogations are conducted in accordance with GMA rules. 
* Interrogation Summary Report (ISR): A report prepared at the conclusion of a source interrogation which contains the specific information obtained during the interrogation as well as a summary of the methods used during the interrogation process and any procedural deviations from GMA rules or relevant operational plans or orders. 
* Human Intelligence (HUMINT): Information collected by human sources such as interviews with captured personnel or individuals with access to enemy communications networks who may provide information on enemy capabilities, dispositions, intentions, activities or plans for their own forces or activities. HUMINT is also used as a source for collecting open-source intelligence (OSINT). 
* OSINT: Information obtained from open-source material such as newspapers, magazines, books, Internet sources, etc., that provides background information about the target environment which can be used to plan military operations. OSINT is also a source for identifying possible sources of HUMINT who may be able to provide additional information on the target environment or specific individuals within it.

Basic Procedures:
1) Interrogation Team Structure: An interrogation team consists of one interrogator and one interpreter unless otherwise authorized by higher authority for a specific mission. The interpreter must be qualified linguistically for the language spoken by captured personnel being interrogated and must also be trained in conducting interviews according to established procedures and policies concerning respect for human rights and ethical considerations. For interrogations conducted in languages other than English, interpreters must have training equivalent to that provided to American Sign Language interpreters at Fort Sam Houston Texas through their training program conducted at Fort Bragg North Carolina at Fort Benning
